# Bump + restart local (full workflow)

## “Bump and ship” (explicit) — GitHub installer (**no remote `dev`**)

A **`dev`** branch on GitHub is **not** required. Local development uses **`scripts/dev-start.ps1`** and a local DB; **Releases** come from **tags** + **Build installer**.

When the user says **“bump and ship”** (bump version, push, queue **GitHub** installer):

1. **Bump** — **`VERSION`** + **`CHANGELOG.md`** `[Unreleased]` → dated **`[X.Y.Z]`** section.
2. **Commit** — On a **named release branch** (e.g. **`git fetch origin && git switch -c release/vX.Y.Z origin/master`**, then commit).
3. **Ship** — From repo root: **`.\scripts\ship-release.ps1`** (requires **`gh auth login`**). It **pushes `HEAD` → `origin/<current-branch>`** and **`gh workflow run "Tag release (from VERSION)" --ref <that-branch>`**, which creates **`vX.Y.Z`** if missing and **dispatches Build installer**.
4. **PR `release/v…` → `master`** — Remind the user to merge when **`master`** should match (protected branch).
5. **`gh workflow run build-installer.yml --ref vX.Y.Z`** — Only as **recovery** (see **`.cursor/rules/github-installer-workflow-ref-trap.mdc`**).

If they also want a local dev server restart, run **`scripts/dev-start.ps1`** after.

---

When the user asks to **bump** (version/release) **and restart local**, or clearly means the same (e.g. “ship it”, “release bump”, “bump and restart”, “new build on GitHub”) **and did not say “bump and ship”**, do **all** of the following unless they explicitly opt out of one step:

1. **Bump** — Update repo `VERSION` and move `CHANGELOG.md` `[Unreleased]` into a dated `[X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD` section (per `CHANGELOG.md` “Releasing”).
2. **Commit** — On a **release branch only** (see below), `git add` the release-related changes (typically `VERSION`, `CHANGELOG.md`, and any code/docs in that release), message e.g. `Release vX.Y.Z` or `chore: release vX.Y.Z — …`.
3. **Branch + push (avoid local `master` mess)** — **`master`** is **protected** on **`jampat000/Grabby`**: **never** commit the release directly on local **`master`** (that leaves you **ahead of `origin/master`** and duplicate history vs the PR).
   - **Do:** `git fetch origin && git switch -c release/vX.Y.Z origin/master` (or `chore/release-vX.Y.Z` if you prefer that naming), then bump/commit on **that** branch, `git push -u origin release/vX.Y.Z`, open PR → merge on GitHub.
   - **After merge:** `git fetch origin && git switch master && git reset --hard origin/master` (or `git pull --ff-only`), then `git branch -d release/vX.Y.Z`. If the remote branch still exists, `git push origin --delete release/vX.Y.Z`.
   - **If push to `master` was rejected:** Do **not** leave local **`master`** carrying the release commit; create **`release/vX.Y.Z`** from **`origin/master`**, cherry-pick or re-apply the bump commit if needed, push the branch, then **`git switch master && git reset --hard origin/master`**.
   - **Do not skip push** of the release branch unless the user says not to or auth/network fails—report errors clearly. Give the **“Open a pull request”** URL; merge with **`gh pr merge`** when available (`%ProgramFiles%\GitHub CLI\gh.exe`) or tell the user to merge on GitHub.
4. **Installer build on GitHub (required)** — After **`vX.Y.Z`** exists on **`origin`** (merge to `master` updates **VERSION** → **Tag release** workflow creates the tag; may take **1–3 minutes**):
   - `git fetch origin master --tags`
   - Confirm tag: `git ls-remote origin refs/tags/vX.Y.Z` (or retry fetch after a short wait).
   - **Ref trap (read `.cursor/rules/github-installer-workflow-ref-trap.mdc`):** `gh workflow run … --ref vX.Y.Z` uses **that tag’s commit’s** `.github/workflows/build-installer.yml`. If the tag points to an **old** SHA (before a CI fix), the **release** step can be **skipped** and **Latest** won’t move. Before running **`gh`**, compare: `git rev-parse vX.Y.Z` vs `git rev-parse origin/master` — if they differ, **do not** assume a manual dispatch is enough; fix the tag to the intended **`master`** commit or bump **`VERSION`**.
   - Run **GitHub CLI** (use full path if `gh` is not on PATH: **`%ProgramFiles%\GitHub CLI\gh.exe`**), **only** when the tag SHA matches what you intend to ship:

```powershell
$v = (Get-Content -LiteralPath VERSION -Raw).Trim()
$tag = "v$v"
$gh = Join-Path $env:ProgramFiles "GitHub CLI\gh.exe"
& $gh workflow run build-installer.yml --repo jampat000/Grabby --ref $tag
```

   - Paste the **run URL** from `gh` output (or `gh run list --workflow=build-installer.yml --repo jampat000/Grabby -L 1`) so the user can watch **Build installer** finish and get **`GrabbySetup.exe`** on **Releases**.
   - If **`gh`** is missing or not logged in (`gh auth login`), say so and give the same command for them to run.
   - **Duplicate runs** (Tag release also dispatches the workflow) are OK — concurrency groups limit overlap; the important part is **a build always queues** from a **correct** tag commit.

5. **Restart local** — Restart the dev server (**`scripts/dev-start.ps1`** from repo root). **8766** = dev source vs **8765** = installed service.

Do **not** treat “bump / release / new build” as complete without **push** and **queuing the installer workflow** (step 4), when the user expects an installable build.

## When done — tell the user (every time)

After the steps above, **briefly confirm**:

1. **Version** — `VERSION` = **X.Y.Z**, `CHANGELOG.md` updated.
2. **GitHub** — Branch pushed / PR merged; **Actions → Build installer** run started (**link**).
3. **Install** — When the run is **green**, **`GrabbySetup.exe`** is under **Releases** for **`vX.Y.Z`** (or **Latest**).
4. **Local** — Dev URL (**8766** default) and restart if they use source.

## Full end-to-end (“new version + installer + local dev”)

1. Release branch → PR → **merge** to **`master`**.
2. **`git fetch origin --tags`** → **`gh workflow run build-installer.yml --repo jampat000/Grabby --ref vX.Y.Z`** (after tag exists).
3. **`git pull origin master`** locally.
4. **`scripts/dev-start.ps1`**.

**Run** terminal steps (including **`gh workflow run`**) for the user when possible—don’t only describe them.
